<TITLE> Nation pays tributes to martyred intellectuals </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 14 (bdnews24.com)The nation is observing Martyred Intellectuals' Day on Monday, paying homage to the memory of the university professors and teachers, scientists, doctors, writers and artists who were brutally killed just days before Bangladesh achieved victory in 1971. The day is being observed amid growing demand for trial of war criminals who annihilated the country's top intellectuals and professionals on this day at the fag end of the liberation war. Marking the day, President Zillur Rahman paid tributes at the Martyred Intellectuals' Memorial at Mirpur in the capital at 7am. Later, prime minister Sheikh Hasina and opposition leader Khaleda Zia also paid their tributes to the martyred intellectuals. Sensing certain defeat in the liberation war, Pakistan occupation forces, abetted by their local collaboratorsthe Rajakars, Al-Badr and Al-Shamshad carried out the killing mission to cripple the new nation. Bodies of renowned intellectuals were found with eyes blindfolded and hands tied in a brickfield in the capital, now known as the Rayerbazar Killing Ground. Different political parties and organisations have taken up programmes marking the day. Awami League, the party that led the war of independence, has arranged programmes including hoisting of black flags and keeping the national flag and party flag at half-mast at the party's headquarter and other offices across the country. The ruling party leaders and activists were to lay wreaths at the Martyred Intellectuals, Memorial at Mirpur, Rayerbazar Killing Ground and on Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman's portrait at Dhanmondi in the morning. The Awami League will hold a discussion meeting at Bangabandhu International Conference Centre at 3pm to pay tributes to the martyred intellectuals. The Sector Commanders Forum will pay tributes at the Rayerbazar Killing Ground at 4pm and form a human chain in the city, demanding speedy trial of war criminals. Some 10,000 law enforcers have been deployed to ensure security in and around the capital. National leaders have issued messages to mark the solemn occasion. In his message, president Zillur Rahman said the memory of those who died for the country's liberation should serve as the conscience of the nation. In her message, prime minister Sheikh Hasina called on all to build a non-communal state inspired by the ideals of the martyred intellectuals. Leader of the opposition Khaleda Zia in her message said the occupation forces wanted to hinder the progress of the new nation by killing the worthy sons of the soil. bdnews
